    "summary": "Gudea was the ruler of the Sumerian city-state of Lagash, reigning approximately 2144–2124 BC during the period between the fall of the [[event:45|Akkadian Empire]] and the rise of the [[event:1724|Third Dynasty of Ur]]. He is one of the most richly documented rulers of the ancient Near East, known primarily through his extensive building inscriptions and a remarkable series of diorite statues depicting him in a pious, worshipful pose. These statues, many of which survive in the Louvre and other major collections, represent some of the finest examples of ancient Mesopotamian sculpture.\n\nGudea's reign was characterized by an ambitious temple-building program, most notably the reconstruction of the temple of the city god Ningirsu at Girsu. His Cylinder Inscriptions, among the longest Sumerian literary texts known, describe in vivid detail the divine mandate he received to build the temple and the resources he gathered from across the ancient world — cedar wood from Lebanon, diorite from Magan, gold and precious stones from distant lands. Though Lagash was a relatively small state, Gudea's inscriptions and artworks have given him an outsized presence in the historical record, making him a central figure in the study of Sumerian religion, art, and statecraft.",
